23. Rhoetum. The giant slain by Bacchus is elsewhere called Eurytus, whereas Rhoetus was a Centaur who fought with the Lapithae (Verg. Georg. 11. 456). Horace however names Rhoetus among the giants again in 111. 4. 55. The legend that Bacchus changed himself into a lion is not found elsewhere.

27. idem. ‘Thou wast the same in the midst of peace and of war.' For the position of -que cf. l. 32 and 1. 30. 6: 'also curatve in 11. 7. 25. The meaning apparently is that Bacchus was always the leader‚ whether of the dance or the combat.

It is to be observed that, as wine makes some men quarrelsome, others merry, the worship of Bacchus was introduced into Greece in two forms, a savage and brutal form which came by way of Thrace, and a mild and cheersul form which came from the South. Both forms existed together in Attica. The logends concerning the god, similarly, represent him now as kind aud beneficent‚ now as cruel and blood- thirsty. The late Mr Pater, ariting on the Bacchae of Euripides, sa “Dionysus Omophagus, the eater of raw flesh, must be added to e golden image of Dionysus Meilichius, the honey-sweet,'' if we are to form a clear idea of the place of the god in Greek religion. See also L. Dyer’s The Gods in Greece, pp. 75-117.
